        <h3>Etiquette</h3>
        <h1>Quite Hour</h1>
      <img src="/clockGermany.jpg" alt="clock" class="smaller-image">
      <p>In Germany, there are designated "quiet hours" (Ruhezeit), usually observed between 1:00 pm and 3:00 pm and after 10:00 pm. During these times, especially in residential areas, people are expected to keep noise levels to a minimum.  </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>This includes refraining from loud activities like lawn mowing, home repairs, or playing loud music. Quiet hours are in place to ensure a peaceful and restful environment for residents. It's important for visitors to be aware of and respect these quiet hours, particularly if staying in accommodations or neighborhoods where they apply. Violating quiet hours can be considered inconsiderate and disruptive to the local community.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Gifts</h1>
        <img src="/gatherGermany.jpg" alt="Photography of People" class="smaller-image">
      <p>Punctuality is a fundamental aspect of German culture. Germans place a strong emphasis on arriving on time for appointments, meetings, and social gatherings. Being late without a valid reason is considered disrespectful and inconsiderate. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> To demonstrate respect and professionalism, it's important to plan your schedule effectively and make every effort to arrive at your destination on time. If you anticipate being delayed, it's polite to inform the other party as soon as possible. Being punctual is seen as a sign of reliability and a good way to make a positive impression in German culture.</p>
